Rules restricting the financing of European football clubs will not in any way disrupt Neymar's record-breaking transfer from Barcelona to Paris-Saint Germain, France.
Any penalty for Paris Saint-Germain will be implemented by the EUFA, which oversees European football teams and has the power to ban teams from participating in the prestigious Champions League.
The Financial Fair Play (FFP) rules that introduced UEFA in 2011 stipulate that PSG will have to prove that Neymar's transfer was not financed without major losses.
Barcelona paid €222 million just to buy Neymar out of his contract and Neymar will demand a salary of several tens of millions of dollars a year.
This is followed by several financial conditions of Neymar's transfer to France.
With the PSG team being funded by a wealthy Qatari family that has made it rich in energy sales, it can afford to bring Neymar into an already stellar football family.
Clubs can spend huge amounts on the purchase of players, but on the other hand, they have to prove legal sources of income, allowing them to cover the overheads of business activities related to football.
FFP introduced Michel Platini after being put in the UEFA director's seat in 2007.
The former French player believed that clubs that would become indebted in the pursuit of new reinforcements ultimately cheat and risk bankruptcy if banks or owners refused to secure them.
In 2011, FFP rules redirected its attention from club debts to monitor their losses.
This change meant that the business model used by Roman Abramovich with Chelsea in 2003 - to buy a club with potential and spent exorbitant sums on players to build a global brand - suddenly it was not so profitable.
As part of the current three-year trial period ending in 2018, clubs can report a loss of up to EUR 30 million.
And despite the fact that Platini had to leave his post in 2015, his successor Aleksander Chefferin is determined to advocate a ban on excessive spending.
“The FFP rules still apply and we are committed to strengthening them in the future,” Andrea Traverso told the Associated Press last week.
Although PSG has paid the amount for the purchase of Neymar in a one-time payment, it may spread the amount over the entire duration of the contract for the purposes of accounting.
Neymar signed a five-year contract, so the transfer can be broken down at EUR 44.4 million each year for five years.
The first wave of the highest sanctions FFP hit PSG in 2014, along with Manchester City, owned by the Abu Dhabi group.
PSG received a fine of EUR 60 million ($82 million) - which was later reduced to €20 million - and an order to reduce the Champions League team to 21 players in the 2014-2015 season, instead of 25 players.
UEFA is wary of teams that may try to circumvent financial regulators by increasing their income through companies associated with club owners.
Thus, even if the Qatari company sponsors PSG once the financing exceeds the value of the standard market rate, UEFA has the right to prohibit the billing of the amount.
A similar measure was taken by UEFA in 2014 after deciding that the amount of funding provided by the PSG's Qatar Tourism Authority was too high.
According to some reports, part of Neymar's revenue in PSG could be paid from the organizational committee of the 2022 FIFA World Cup in Qatar.
However, PSG and the leaders of the 2022 World Cup in Qatar denied the fact that Neymat should become an ambassador for the World Cup in football and that such a maneuver would be easily detected by UEFY officials.
Previous sanctions imposed on PSG mean that UEFA will closely monitor any attempt to circumvent the rules,
