NHS Prescribes Controversial HIV Drug 10 000 Patients
Patients will have access to ‘transformative’ treatment to HIV prevention from September based on a decision by the Supreme Court to finance the NHS.
The National Health Service (NSH) has announced that the pre-exposure prophylaxis (PreP) pill, which is taken before sex and reduces the risk of infection in high-risk patients by up to 86 percent, will be offered through health service to approximately 10,000 patients within a three-year probationary period.
The NSH agreed to finance the probationary period after the Court of Appeal supported the Supreme Court's decision last year, stating that the NHS has funds to pay for the PreP despite statements that the drug should be financed by local authorities.
The decision, announced on Thursday, was taken by England from the mouth of CEO Simon Stevens as a 'significant intervention' while the National Aids Trust (NAT) described the decision as a 'decisive moment'.
Sexual health clinics in London, Brighton, Manchester, Liverpool and Sheffield will be among the first to start accepting patients. Other clinics will join in October and will be fully implemented across England by April 2018.
Pre-exposure prophylaxis (PreP) is an HIV drug given before sex to reduce the risk of HIV.
Tests have shown that the PEP significantly reduces the risk of HIV transmission among vulnerable patients.
The application of PrEP before sex means that there is a sufficient amount of specific drugs in the patient's body to prevent infection.
These medications can be taken every day or at least two hours before sex.
Tested patients include homosexuals or bisexual men, transgender people and people with HIV-positive partners who are not treated successfully.
The clinics shall identify eligible participants who sign consent to participation in testing, including men, women, transgender people and individuals with a partner whose HIV status is not yet controlled by appropriate treatment.
People living and registered with the UK GP can also apply in their local sexual health clinic and apply for potential participation in testing.
The program will cost taxpayers £10 million, and NHS England signed a contract this week to distribute medicines after winning an international public contract.
The trial period is proposed to collect clinical evidence and assess the full potential of the PREA, its targeting, use and implementation on a large scale.
Simon Stevens added: ‘This important intervention should complement and fully exploit the ever-expanding and increasingly successful efforts to prevent HIV.
It is another milestone in more than thirty years of trying to stop one of the greatest challenges to human health.'
Deborah Gold, NAT (National Aids Trust), said: ‘We are witnessing a decisive moment in the fight against HIV.
If the PrEP is administered correctly and at risk for patients, it will offer the possibility of a transformation of the English HIV epidemic.
From September, NSH will offer patients who are at high risk of HIV infection with a new powerful tool that is individually controlled and not subject to the need to persuade a partner, which will lead to an improvement in the quality of many lives.
We accept this statement with pleasure.'
Ian Green, Chief Executive Officer of the Terrence Higgins Trust, said: ‘Priority number one must be the rapid deployment of tests across the country; we must ensure its availability to each patient.
Now we have a prep test drug available and we are well on our way to protect more than 10 000 people who are at risk of HIV infection.'
Shadow Health Minister Sharon Hodgson said: ‘The start of the prePE exam period is a welcome and long-awaited change after months of delays and delays by the government.
Evidence suggests how transformative this drug may be as part of our approach to HIV prevention and termination of transmission of this life-threatening infection.
Subsequent tests will take us one step closer to a full understanding of the benefits of the PrEP.
It is now important that we start the tests as soon as possible across the country to protect those exposed to HIV and together end the spread of HIV in society.'
