An article in the journal Current Biology reported that it was the 'most preserved armored dinosaur found so far and one of the best dinosaur species in the world'.
Petty is a new kind of family Nodosauridae. Dinosaur lived in the Cretaceous period, about 110 to 112 million years ago.
His perfectly preserved condition literally shocked the researchers, who described him with the words 'really remarkable'.
According to National Geographic, the armored birch-grandfaper is still the best preserved fossil of its kind.
Behind the find is Shawn Funk, who uncovered the fossil on March 21, 2011 during drilling at the Suncor Millenium mine near Alberta, Canada.
He came across something that looked like a foreign object and decided to explore it more closely.
The fossil was shipped to the Royal Tyrrell Museum of Paleontology.
The researchers spent the next six years working to uncover an animal from a huge piece of land weighing 1100 kg.
After the work is completed, the dinosaur is ready to be discovered.
“All you have to do is squint a little and you will believe that he is asleep,” said the head of work Caleb Brown and the naturalist of the Royal Tyrrell Museum, where the animal is on display.
“I’m sure he’ll go down in history as one of the most beautiful and survived dinosaur species – the Mona Lisa dinosaurs.”
By studying his skin, the researchers found that this herbivore - despite being covered with armor and resembling a walking tank - most likely faced a serious threat from carnivorous dinosaurs.
The heavily armored dinosaur used red and white camouflage to protect against predators and used a camouflage system used by many animals today.
Experts say it allowed him to merge better with his surroundings and avoid enemies. The camouflage system suggests it was a favorite food of larger dinosaurs.
Reports of the 110-million-year-old dinosaur family Nodosauridae first appeared in newspapers in May. It is currently available at the Royal Tyrrell Museum of Palaeontology.
The researchers named him Borealoppelta markmitchelli after museum technician Mark Mitchell, who, along with the team, spent more than 7000 hours carefully uncovering the fossil.
Thanks to the amazingly preserved state of the fossil, dr. Mitchell and an international team of scientists to document the patterns and shape of the scales and armor throughout the body.
They revealed the method of camouflage commonly used by today's animals in defense - the upper part of the animal was darker than its lower part.
Although this camouflage effect is common in nature, the researchers' findings are surprising because Borealopleta's size far exceeds today's animals using the same technique.
It is therefore possible that the dinosaur was so many predators that evolution preferred to camouflage to confrontation in survival.
Many contemporary animals with camouflage - for example, deer, zebra or shingle - are much smaller and also more vulnerable as prey, suggesting that the nosodaur had to literally fight for its outgoing.
“The predation of a huge and heavily armored dinosaur illustrates the danger posed by predators in the Cretaceous period,” Brown said.
A chemical analysis of the organic ingredients contained in scales also revealed that dinosaur skins had a reddish-brown coloration.
Researchers continue to study the animal and search for more knowledge of his life, including the preserved contents of the stomach, to track down his last meal.
He believes the dinosaur fell into a river after death and was taken to the sea, where it sanched to the bottom.
In the Alberta region at that time, the same climate was as in present-day Florida, and rivers, and the oceans stretched much further into the inland than it is today.
“This nodosaurus is truly remarkable in that it is completely covered in perfectly preserved scaly skin and is preserved in three dimensions and we can see its original size,” Brown said.
“For these reasons, the animal looks practically the same as in the time of chalk.
