Red meat, dairy products and chocolate can alleviate the symptoms of inflammatory bowel diseases (IBD)
For your digestive system, red meat and dairy products can be a nightmare.
However, the new study suggests the opposite: a diet rich in animal protein and dairy products could help relieve the symptoms of inflammatory bowel diseases.
An incurable disease, affecting up to 1.3 million U.S. people and 300 000 patients in the UK, causes abdominal pain and bloody diarrhea, weight loss and extreme fatigue.
Patients are usually reminded of not incipient meat and dairy products to relieve symptoms. However, University researchers at Washington found that the essential amino acid tryptophan contained in the protein helps to create immune cells that promote bowel resistance.
Head of study dr. Marco Colonna explained that immune cells protect the intestines and ensure the breakdown of harmful microbes from food.
The number of inflammatory cells is balanced by the number of cells that promote tolerance and protect the body without damaging sensitive tissue.
Once the scales tilt sided with inflammation, inflammatory bowel disease may occur.
As part of the research, the researchers found the presence of immune cells supporting the body's tolerance in the stomach of a mouse with a specific bacteria.
This bacterium requires the presence of tryptophan - one of the building blocks of proteins to form cells.
Professor Colonna said: "We found a link between one kind of bacteria - Lactobacillus reuteri - which is a common part of the intestinal microbiome and the development of cells that promote the body's tolerance.
The more tryptophan the mice had in their diet, the more they had these immune cells."
At the same time, he suggested that if the same goes for a human, then the combination of L. reuteri and a tryptophan-rich-rich diet would help develop a more tolerant and less inflammatory intestinal environment.
Graduate researcher dr. As part of studying a certain type of immune cells supporting the body’s tolerance, Luisa Cervantes-Barraganwas discovered that one group of test mice had these cells, while the other group of the same mice was missing cells.
She deduced from the fact that one group of mice has a different gut microbiome - a community of bacteria, viruses and fungi that normally dwell in the gastrointestinal tract.
The mouse intestines were tested by the DNA alignment method, and researchers found six kinds of bacteria in mics with immune cells, which were lacking in the second group of mics.
The mice that were bred in a sterile environment and lacked an intestinal microbiome - so they did not develop this kind of immune cells - the bacterium L. reuteri - and formed immune cells.
To understand how bacteria affect the immune system, researchers developed L. reuteri in the fluid and then transferred a small amount of fluid - without bacteria - undeveloped immune cells that were kept in isolation.
Immune cells have evolved into tolerant cells.
After removing the active ingredient from the liquid, it turned out to be a byproduct of tryptophanous metabolism known as indoll-yestic acid.
When researchers doubled the amount of tryptophan in the mice, the amount of these cells increased by 50 percent. At the same time, after the dose of tryptophan, the number of cells dropped by half.
Dr. Cervantes-Barragan explained that people have the same tolerant cells as mice, and most of us keep the bacteria L. reuteri in their gastrointestinal tract.
It is not known if tryptophane byproducts from L. reuteri cause cell development in humans in the same way as in mice, but defects in the genes related to tryptophan were detected in people with inflammatory bowel disease.
Dr. Cervantes-Barragan added: "Each of us should probably strive to develop these cells because they control the inflammatoryness of the inner bowel.
The potentially high level of tryptophan in the presence of L. reuteri can increase the population of cells."
