British inventor uses a microchip in his hand to unlock a car and house with a wave
The British inventor became the first man in the country with a microchip put into the body. With a simple wave of his hand, he can unlock the door from the house and office and even start a car.
Thirty-three-year-old Steven Northam has had a tiny chip implanted between his thumb and index finger and currently offers the same service through his company BioTeq to companies and individuals who want to simplify their lives using technology.
The procedure of implantation and adherence to treatment procedures is supervised by dr. Geoff Watson, anesitisologist at Royal Hampshire County Hospital in Winchester.
The technology works on the same principle as microchips implanted with dogs and cats, and the whole procedure takes 30 seconds.
The Northam company also offers a service to replace door and car locks with a microchip. The price of one castle is £300.
The married father of one child has integrated the technology into his house and his BMW Z4 car, which he starts with a simple wave of his hand.
White House Prop Cost Taxpayers Thousands of Dollars
The White House's decision to fly with the Navy helicopter to South Lawn to mark the U.S. manufacturing industry celebration last month came at $24, according to the Navy's records issued by the weekly TIME.
The green white helicopter Sikorsky VH-3D, also called Marine One in the presence of the president on board, was the highlight of the program of 17. July at the White House, which was a parade of U.S. design programs.
President Donald Trump, Vice President Mike Pence and several senior White House officials surveyed a product show of 50 states.
The Connecticut helicopter was displayed alongside a Yacht from Maine, a Wisconsin fire truck and a forkliftlift truck from Mississippi.
A White House military officer issued a fragmentary order, or FRAGO, and asked for the presence of a helicopter less than 36 hours before the helicopter landed on South Lawn as part of an "extraordinary" event, the records of Marine Helicopter Squadron One (HMX-1) - units responsible for the administration of the helicopter said.
"I wanted to make sure that you have an awareness of such a significant event," the HMX-1 commander wrote in an email to his superior, a representative of the aviation navy commander the day before the event began.
The report suggested that the helicopter will arrive at South Lawn 17. July approximately at 7:00 on the occasion of the parade, the start of which is scheduled for 15:00 and will remain in place until the entire site was completely evacuated, which was planned between 18:00 and 21:00.
The email further stated that if there was a delay on departure from the White House, a replacement crew would be sent for the return flight due to working hours.
The original crew remained in place that evening along with the helicopter, and with them a unit of security personnel.
From the records - obtained by the weekly TIME - it was not apparent whether the second crew was eventually sent.
The Hatch Act prevents civil servants from using government property for political purposes.
The records indicate that HMX-1 is investigating a possible violation of this regulation.
"We wondered if it was a violation of the Hatch Act and we were assured that everything was fine," the commander wrote.
"It sounds like you're blocked," the deputy commander wrote.
This "Made in America" parade was marked by the White House as an official event, and the Hatch Act would not apply to it.
But even official events have political subtexts.
In his participation in the event, the president advocated a medical reform that passed through the Senate and spoke of an effort to keep government regulations at bay.
The use of air vehicles such as Marine One or Air Force One for political purposes is hardly a new phenomenon.
Presidents use them when traveling.
However, their presence is unusual for presentation reasons.
Trump ordered control in February after the presidential plane was driving in the background at his first rally as part of a campaign in Melbourne, Florida. His Twitter account is overwhelmed by complaints about the use of the presidential plane by his predecessors.
“The White House is delighted with the ‘Made in America’ show, which introduced products from all 50 states made by Americans from American materials,” said Lindsay Walters, a representative of the press secretary.
HMX-1 helicopter crews often train landings in the Washington and South Lawn region, reticing potential arrivals with the President of the United States to the White House with maximum accuracy.
While Trump took part in the G-20 summit in Germany in early July, HMX-1 conducted 58 practice landings at the White House.
The flight to the Made in America show was part of the crew's current training session, the state official said.
The helicopter unit flew another eleven hours as part of “non-Presidential Support Missions” on the same day.
The White House said no additional props were covered by taxpayers' money.
A Sikorsky spokesman said the company was not involved in any way in negotiations to expose the helicopter to South Lawn.
HMX-1 does not keep the records of the presidential flight budget, and the exact costs related to the parade are, according to the Navy, difficult to determine.
According to the Defense Department, the hourly price for fiscal year 2017, DoD's refunds on VH-3D 24,380 dollars per flight hour.
Records of the unit indicate a time of 30 minutes from the Marine Corps Air Facility Quantico in Virginia and back.
The White House argues that the actual operating costs of the helicopter are well below that amount.
"Indicating the costs of taxpayers based on estimates for reimbursement of expenses is very misleading," Walters said.
"These estimates include staff, maintenance and many other hidden costs included in the annual cost."
According to the 2015 RAND study, DoD’s reimbursement does not include staff costs, but include fuel prices, maintenance and contractual costs.
The White House press secretary of the Sean Spicer defended the use of a helicopter for the purpose of the parade.
"The idea of the parade that takes place this week is to introduce products made in the U.S.," Spicer said.
“I am aware that Sikorsky and the state of Connecticut are very proud of the fact that they contribute to the defense of our state, and that they provide the work of hundreds, if not thousands, of people.
I think, like most Americans, that we are proud of the helicopter and other military facilities, the production of which is involved in countless American citizens.
This is to be remembered.”
It is unclear if Trump, during his roundabout on South Lawn, also looked at the helicopter. It is certain that he sat behind the wheel of one of the fire trucks.
Back at the White House, Trump addressed Sikorsky representatives and joked with the media about his own fleet of products.
"I know Sikorsky very well," the president said, "I own three of them himself."
