Police dogs trained in Most overflight by helicopter
Dogs specialized in searching explosives and search dogs today re-exerted at Lake Most by helicopter overflight.
The police dog must not be timid and afraid of flying, said the head of the police cynologists of the Ústí Region, Petr Tomášek.
The training of a police dog takes about two years.
At Most, both adults trained trained dogs and those who are just undergoing training.
In addition to the standard training, in which they were supposed to detect sharp samples of explosives in the vicinity of the lake and search for a lost figure, all 12 animals had to board a helicopter and fly over the lake.
The main purpose of the exercise is to test dogs in a helicopter.
So that immediately the helicopter gets, the dog can go to work, so that he does not have a problem with the helicopter's journey.
"A helicopter gets down, the dog goes and immediately searches," Tommy said.
A dog that is restless or unable to start working immediately on the way by helicopter is eliminated from the training.
"Mostly they are left by dog handlers, for example, in the garden," Tommy added.
The police have 76 dogs in the Ústí nad Labem region with various specializations.
German shepherds are predominant, but there are also more Belgian shepherds.
The handler takes care of him from the puppy.
"He educates him himself, prepares it for the service that the dog will do for us," Tomášek added.
The animal undergoes repeated veterinary examinations, which can detect possible medical disabilities.
If the dog is healthy and unfageted, it passes the first exams at 20 months.
"He is getting into a sharp intervention around two and a half to three years," Tomášek added.
The length of the police service depends on the health of the dog.
It usually serves up to eight to ten years.
They usually live in their handlers.
