According to the UN, Afghan Democracy relies on women in politics
Elections can only be credible if all members of society, including women, are taking part in them, a representative of the UN in Afghanistan said on Wednesday.
Nicholas Haysom, senior official of the United Nations Auxiliary Mission, said hundreds of women are taking part in the election to local councils, three women are applying for the post of vice president, and more than 30 percent of newly registered voters are women.
"The role of women cannot be overlooked," he said in a statement on Wednesday.
Elections can be fully representative and trustworthy only if women, as well as all related processes related to the election, take part in them.
The local and presidential elections in Afghanistan will take place on April 5.
The Taliban has released several threats against the electoral process, which is shifting international combat activities to the other side.
In this year’s elections, for the first time, one democratically elected government passes on its power to the following government.
Haysom said the strong role of women will strengthen Afghanistan's democracy.
The Afghan Independent Election Commission said of the total 3.6 million registered voters make up 1.2 million women.
The unique brewery brews beer again.
For a good beer in a resurrected brewery.
The enthusiasm and honesty of the new owners returned to life a few years ago the brewery in Lobč u Mšena.
The brewery, commemorated for the first time in 1586, has a Renaissance core and was converted into a steam engine operation in the 19th century.
It was followed by years of heyday, when the brewery was famous mainly for dark beers.
Unfortunately, during the Second World War, production was stopped and in 1984 the brewery was nationalized.
Since then, the buildings have served the state farm.
The work of destruction was completed by the owners of the brewery after 1989.
The abandoned area was devastated and dismantsed into building material.
In 2007, however, there was a new hope in the form of new owners, architects Jana and Pavel Prouz.
They began to repair the buildings with the utmost respect for the spirit of the building and every detail.
They have been carefully engaged and devoted to the study of archival materials, trying to preserve the original materials and building elements.
The brewery takes the same form as in the nineteenth century, when its golden era started.
Their work was awarded by the brewery's declaration of a cultural monument by the Ministry of Culture and the building also became part of the European Industrial Heritage Trails.
In 2015, they also ceremonially renewed the tradition of brewing beer.
If you want to taste great Lobeč beer in the picturesque landscape of Kokořínsko, visit the bar in the brewery area.
When brewing beer, they use kokořín water springing in the protected landscape area, malt from the Lobec fields and Žatec hops.
In the bar you will taste traditional pale lager, but also dark beers and specials.
And do not miss a tour of the brewery, it takes place on Saturday and Sunday at noon and half past two.
