Get to know the plant with one click.
The new free application Pl@ntNet will help students with the creation of herbariums and ordinary plant lovers.
When they are interested in what plant they have just come across a walk, this application will advise them.
All they will have to do is photograph the plant, and the app itself will recognize what kind it is.
The new application, which is available for both iOS and Android, was introduced on Tuesday by representatives of the CEEV Ethical and Environmental Education Center in Bratislava’s Mountain Park as part of the Secret Life of the City project.
Pupils from 50 Czech and Slovak schools were also involved in the project, who photographed with teachers in the database of the application and added plants from their surroundings.
The newly created French app is free to download on the website The Secret Life of the City.
The main goal of French programmers was to make as many people as possible contribute to the application with their images, and thus increase the number of plants that the application can recognize.
"Already children who can keep a tablet or mobile phone in their hands can go to the forest," said Ivana Poláčková, the coordinator of this project.
Based on a sufficiently high-quality photo of the flower, leaf or fruit of the plant, the application can recognize its name in a few seconds, which then assigns it under the photo in Czech and Slovak.
The French have allowed us to translate the application into Slovak and Czech into the project The Secret Life of the City.
It is therefore welcomed that users after opening the account to the application contribute to the application by a picture of a plant that is not yet present in the database.
"The French will evaluate if it is beneficial, and then they will add it to the database," Poláčková said.
