The unions are demanding assurances from the managers of the biscuit maker McVitie's about the long-term commitment of production at the factory in Glasgow.
The Scottish trade union GMB said the company was silent for the time being about a possible investment in the Tollcross factory.
There are more than 500 employees working in the factory, who, among other products, also make Hobnob and Rich Tea biscuits.
The owner of McVitie's, the company Pladis, said it had invested more than £5 million in the area in the past few years.
She added that the employees and representatives of the unions would be "among the first informed" in the event of changes in the operation of the factory.
In a letter to the company's construction manager, the Scottish GMB union expressed their concerns that McVitie's "will not get their promises to fund and upgrade production lines."
GMB’s chief organizer, Drew Duffy, added: “The fact that we have not received a clear response from the construction manager regarding the company’s needs and the future investment plan in Tollcross is very worrying for our members.
Generations of many families have worked here, and employees come mostly from the local community and Glasgow, where work at the factory here represents a critical pillar of decent employment in the area of high unemployment and social separation.
From the point of view of work, salaries and benefits - and despite the outlook for Brexit, the rising cost of living and declining slow production - the eastern part of Glasgow needs a desperately prosperous producer like McVitie's."
A spokeswoman for Pladis said: "The Tollcross construction manager received a letter from GMB only yesterday and the company will issue a statement as soon as possible as we value the continued commitment to the union's employees and representatives.
A regular meeting with GMB staff and representatives of GMB in Tollcross was held two months ago, and at this meeting, many problems were openly talked about.
We talked to employees that, as in all companies operating in extremely competitive and uncertain economic conditions, we evaluate our operation on a regular basis, which applies to all our operations so that we can continue to compete successfully for others.
She added: “In recent years, we have invested £5 million in Tollcross, especially in production lines and streamlining operations.
We greatly appreciate the heritage of Tollcross and the locality, and in the event of any changes in the operation of the local factory, the employees and representatives of the unions will be immediately informed."
